Ross Morgan-Linial wrote:
>
>The idea of Plots is to add a sort of 'overflow drain'. If VTs and/or 
>P-Notes are devalued, the value of Indulgences will be higher in 
>comparison. People will change Houses and Farms to Churches 
>(raising the value of Ergs) and Mines, and the abundance of VTs and 
>P-Notes will decline. At least, that's the theory - the only way to 
>check it is to pass Plots, but I believe it will work.

I have another theory: VTs are intrinsically more valuable than either
P-Notes or Indulgences. After all, one can avoid Blots if one is
careful, and not everyone wants to make Proposals. But everyone wants
to vote. Players will therefore hoard VTs for future use, if that is
possible, even if that means having more VTs now than they can use,
and even if it means doing without P-notes and Indulgences.

Now, I'm not sure if I've understood Plots completely, but am I right
in thinking that matters are arranged so that if everyone tries to
produce VTs, there won't be enough Ergs to pay the costs associated
with VT production? If so, that is good. 

